mm/khugepaged: collapse MMF_THP_ALWAYS mms promptly

The PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED flag alone measured *neutral* on the
motivating workload: on-fault THP only covers post-flag faults, and
stock khugepaged -- 10 s scan interval, small per-wakeup budget,
round-robin over every registered mm -- never collapsed the
already-faulted heap within a ~67 s benchmark run (AnonHugePages
stayed flat).  A process that explicitly opted into aggressive THP
wants its existing heap collapsed promptly, not eventually.

Add three mechanisms, all keyed on MMF_THP_ALWAYS and therefore
exactly zero-cost when no process has opted in:

 1. Kick on opt-in: khugepaged_enter_mm(), called from
    prctl(PR_SET_THP_DISABLE, 0, PR_THP_ALWAYS_ADVISED), registers
    the mm with khugepaged (an already-running process may otherwise
    not be registered until its next mmap or huge fault) and wakes
    the daemon.  The wake zeroes khugepaged_sleep_expire first -- as
    every in-tree kick does -- because khugepaged_should_wakeup()
    otherwise ignores a bare wake while a scan_sleep is pending.

 2. Per-mm scan-budget boost: when the current scan slot is a
    flagged mm, raise the per-call budget so a single pass covers
    long runs of scan-only PMDs.  This does not let one mm sweep
    everything in one go -- each attempted collapse still drops
    mmap_lock and returns, and khugepaged_do_scan() still ends the
    wakeup at the global pages_to_scan cap -- and the boost is
    itself capped so one giant flagged mm cannot monopolise a pass.

 3. Sleep-skip while collapsing: when a pass successfully collapsed
    a hugepage in a flagged mm, skip the next scan_sleep throttle
    and run back-to-back.  Self-limiting: the bit clears itself, so
    the normal throttle resumes as soon as collapses stop.

Since khugepaged can now also collapse to sub-PMD (mTHP) orders, the
boosted pass benefits flagged mms whose sysfs configuration enables
mTHP orders as well; nothing here is PMD-specific.

Measured on the motivating workload (Factorio 2.0 headless, Steam
Deck, interleaved A/B, stock global khugepaged tunables, global
enabled=madvise, only the game flagged): +2.53% updates-per-second
(ms/tick 1.4808 -> 1.4443; Welch t=5.79, p<0.0001, n=32/side
interleaved).  Throughput convention, used consistently below: the
UPS gain is the ratio of mean ms/tick, (1.4808 / 1.4443) - 1.  No
interleaved ON block mean was worse than the overall OFF mean (worst
ON block mean 1.4640 vs OFF mean 1.4808).  A global
aggressive-khugepaged configuration puts the ceiling at +5.76% UPS
(ms/tick 1.4853 -> 1.4044, n=18/side).

These numbers were measured on a 6.16.12-valve24.4 (Steam Deck)
kernel carrying an equivalent backport of this series with a
prototype prctl spelling and pre-mTHP khugepaged; this port to the
current tree is build-tested but not yet re-measured.

The gap to the ceiling is honest and understood: the flagged side is
bimodal (sd roughly 5x the unflagged side).  There is no scan-list
reprioritisation, so a freshly flagged mm is still reached in list
order; when its first collapse lands early in a run the win is
large, and when the round-robin position lands it late the run
approaches the unflagged mean.  Bounding time-to-first-collapse
would require reordering the scan list for flagged mms, a fairness
trade-off deliberately not taken here.

Known limitations, documented at the mechanisms in mm/khugepaged.c:
a flagged process that keeps faulting and freeing anonymous memory
can hold khugepaged unthrottled via the sleep-skip (bounded per
collapse attempt by ~max_ptes_none PTEs of scan work; khugepaged
runs at MAX_NICE, so this is a fairness concern, not a liveness
one), and the sleep-skip can carry one stale back-to-back pass
after a flagged process exits.

